init_text:
Is Listening to a Book Just as Good as Reading It?

Do you listen to audiobooks? What are the benefits, in your opinion, of listening instead of reading? Are there advantages to reading that cannot be gained by listening? Which method do you prefer? Why?

---

In my opinion,

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: It is wonderful to listen while doing something else, instead of the usual staring at a page.

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: Surprisingly, it still allows you to absorb the story richly and in the same ways as with reading.

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: The voices of the narrator are so captivating that you begin to almost forget the fact that it's a book, and you are only listening to it

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: I would definitely recommend it to others who feel like they don't have the time to read or would prefer to listen than read.

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: In my opinion, it's just as good, if not better, to listen to than reading the physical copy, if the tale is good enough.

actions.name: text-delete
actions.text: if the tale is good enough.

actions.text: This makes it more convenient for me, especially if I'm on a long trip or doing something else.

actions.text: You can carry around a whole library in your pocket on an mp3 player and can listen to it at the gym, commuting, and multitask with

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: whatever else you may have to do.

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: The voice actors bring the characters to life and take the book to a whole different level.

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: The ability to read in various accents and with different voice levels are only some of the features you get which you wouldn't experience otherwise.

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: I've read hundreds of books in my life, and find that there is a metamorphosis when reading an audiobook.

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: Your mind allows you to visualize the story as if you were watching a movie, and each actor's voice is unique in its presentation - that becomes an

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: added feature you cannot get with a physical book.

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: The young reader can listen to the words in their own voice and that of the narrator's, making them feel more comfortable with spoken language.

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: It also enables them to read along with each character.

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: Audiobooks encourage children to join the book themselves by creating character voices, moving their lips as the characters move theirs, and sneaking a peek at the

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: Any book in the library may be obtained as an audiobook, and there is no waiting list.

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: Audiobooks are also considerably less expensive than print books.

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: A popular print book can cost $15-$20 at the library or other bookstore, but a popular audiobook costs less than $10.

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: There are also numerous free audiobooks in various formats available through our public library.

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: Audiobooks allow you to consume more printed material and explore more subjects than you would otherwise.

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: For example, you might read a magazine article or other short text in your own time, but with audiobooks you can consume a much broader topic

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: You could be listening to a book on beekeeping while you're driving to work, and in the process learn audibly about other books and current issues

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: Audiobooks have the convenience that you can listen to them almost anywhere.

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: Audiobooks give visually impaired people an excellent chance to read.

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: People who have never listened to an audiobook before may be surprised to learn that they are in fact just as good, if not better, than print
